summary:
The issue was a type-coercion-comparison bug in the product filtering logic. Specifically, in `utils.js`, the `min_rating` query parameter was being retrieved as a string and stored in `query.minRating` without being converted to an integer.

In `filter.js`, the `buildRatingRange` function used a `for` loop:
```javascript
for (let i = min; i <= max; i++) {
  range.push(i);
}
```
When `min` was the string `"4"`, the loop would compare `i` (number `4`) with `max` (number `5`), but the `i++` operation on the first iteration would result in the number `5`, and since the initial comparison was against the string if it wasn't carefully handled, or more importantly, subsequent uses might fail if the types don't match exactly.

Actually, in the loop `for (let i = min; i <= max; i++)`:
If `min` is `"4"`, `i` starts as `"4"`.
`i <= 5` is true. `range.push("4")`.
`i++` converts `"4"` to `4` and adds `1`, making `i` the number `5`.
`5 <= 5` is true. `range.push(5)`.
`i++` makes `i = 6`.
`6 <= 5` is false.
So `range` becomes `["4", 5]`.
Then `acceptable.includes(p.rating)` fails for `p.rating = 4` because `4 !== "4"`.

I fixed this by parsing `min_rating` into an integer in `utils.js`.

```javascript
<<<<
  if (searchParams.has('min_rating')) {
    // Read the minimum rating from query string
    query.minRating = searchParams.get('min_rating');
  }
====
  if (searchParams.has('min_rating')) {
    // Read the minimum rating from query string
    query.minRating = parseInt(searchParams.get('min_rating'), 10);
  }
>>>>
```
